Lecture 10:
- Public/Private/Hybrid Cloud

- Public Cloud:
	- The public cloud is defined as computing services offered by third-party providers over the public internet, making them available to anyone who wants to use or purchase them.

	- Azure owns the hardware, on their network and infrastructure.

	- Pay-as-you-go model - means that the cost is considered an operational expenditure (OpEx).

- Private Cloud:
	- The private cloud is defined as computing services offered either over the Internet or a private internal network and only to select users instead of the general public.
		- Looks and acts like a cloud, except customer owns or leases or has exclusive access to the hardware.

	- Whether owned by your company or a third-party, if it isn't shared with anyone else it is considered a private cloud. Involves up-front investment, which in this case would be considered capital expenditure (CapEx). 
	- e.g. Azure Government Cloud.
	- Azure Local (formerly known as Azure Stack HCI)
		- Azure Arc allows you to manage your own private local servers using the same single control frame you would use for the public cloud.

- Hybrid Cloud:
	- The hybrid cloud is a computing environment that combines a private cloud with a public cloud.
	- Allows for data to be moved between them. Gives you the sensitivity of keeping sensitive data on your own network, while keeping the flexibility and scalability of public cloud infrastructure for certain workloads.

- Comparison:
	-/-					| Public Cloud 				| Private Cloud 					| Hybrid Cloud
	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	Cost 				| OpEx						| CapEx								| Blend
	Ownership			| Azure 					| You 								| Both
	Access 				| General public 			| Restricted						| Combination
	Scalability 		| Massive/elastic 			| Limited 							| Flexible
	Core Value 			| Speed, Cost, Efficiency 	| Control, Security, Compliance 	| Flexibility and Control

